WEBVTT

00:01.902 --> 00:04.004
<i>♪ MTV ♪</i>

00:07.275 --> 00:08.809
There were people out there.

00:08.909 --> 00:11.011
<i>Where you said
it was safe to train.</i>

00:11.112 --> 00:12.046
I'll make a call.

00:12.146 --> 00:13.514
<i>The mess will be cleaned.</i>

00:13.614 --> 00:15.749
You think you're
the only one with an army?

00:15.849 --> 00:17.851
Well, that's just a little
nibble of what they can do.

00:17.951 --> 00:20.154
[Jimenez] <i>Call me when
you come home, Tommy.</i>

00:20.254 --> 00:23.656
<i>Or maybe I just come find you.</i>

00:23.657 --> 00:26.860
I am planning on stepping back.

00:26.960 --> 00:29.363
I'm making you
Vice President of Operations.

00:29.497 --> 00:30.864
What are your thoughts
on Rebecca?

00:30.964 --> 00:32.833
The way she works
is a liability.

00:32.933 --> 00:35.135
If she negotiates oil leases
like she litigates,

00:35.136 --> 00:36.803
we won't have
any leases to service.

00:36.804 --> 00:38.539
[Ariana] Studying for a test?

00:38.639 --> 00:40.640
- What's the subject?
- Our future.

00:40.641 --> 00:42.210
I can't trust this right now.

00:42.310 --> 00:43.577
Maybe just focus on
your own life for now.

00:43.677 --> 00:45.246
We'll see where this thing goes.

00:45.379 --> 00:46.847
[Hardin] <i>If you're looking for
work, I ain't got none.</i>

00:46.947 --> 00:48.315
If you're looking
to sell me something,

00:48.316 --> 00:49.482
I ain't got no money
to buy it with.

00:49.483 --> 00:50.683
I'm looking to make you money.

00:50.684 --> 00:51.885
How you gonna do that?

00:52.019 --> 00:54.722
[monitors beeping steadily]

00:54.822 --> 00:56.356
[beeping rapidly]

00:56.357 --> 00:58.658
[grunts]

00:58.659 --> 01:00.193
[labored breathing]

01:00.194 --> 01:03.764
[Monty sighs]

01:06.033 --> 01:09.137
[film reel narrator]
<i>Now, the rest of the story.</i>

01:09.237 --> 01:11.705
<i>And to this one,
let's both pay attention.</i>

01:11.805 --> 01:15.675
<i>What gold was in earlier ages
oil is in these days.</i>

01:15.676 --> 01:17.411
<i>Oil is the paramount factor</i>

01:17.511 --> 01:19.713
<i>in the political economies
of the day.</i>

01:19.813 --> 01:23.383
<i>Besides the material ingredients
of petroleum,</i>

01:23.384 --> 01:24.718
<i>there are involved in it</i>

01:24.818 --> 01:26.787
<i>the moral elements of
peace or war</i>

01:26.920 --> 01:29.557
<i>and friendship or antagonism
between races</i>

01:29.657 --> 01:31.057
<i>and nations and creeds.</i>

01:31.058 --> 01:34.295
<i>Oil may soothe
the troubled waters</i>

01:34.428 --> 01:37.063
<i>of the eternal seas,</i>

01:37.064 --> 01:40.301
<i>but it only adds unrest
to the troubled waters</i>

01:40.401 --> 01:42.236
<i>of international diplomacy.</i>

01:42.336 --> 01:44.905
<i>Oil has become the great</i>

01:45.005 --> 01:47.641
<i>international issue of the hour.</i>

01:47.775 --> 01:50.578
<i>It lurks in the background
of virtually every problem</i>

01:50.678 --> 01:53.947
<i>now engaging the attention
of world statesmen.</i>

01:54.047 --> 01:56.784
<i>Politics has become
the politics of petroleum.</i>

01:56.917 --> 02:01.087
<i>Almost no move is made
on that chessboard</i>

02:01.088 --> 02:02.756
<i>that is not tinctured with oil,</i>

02:02.856 --> 02:04.825
<i>including the pending situation</i>

02:04.925 --> 02:07.595
<i>in the near east, all the way
from the Persian Gulf</i>

02:07.695 --> 02:09.330
<i>to the Golden Horn.</i>

02:09.430 --> 02:12.333
<i>But I'm telling you pretty much
what you already know, am I not?</i>

02:13.901 --> 02:15.603
<i>I mean, you know
that we need to conserve.</i>

02:15.703 --> 02:17.871
<i>You know that gas prices
are intolerably high.</i>

02:17.971 --> 02:21.442
<i>You know that oil
and international unrest</i>

02:21.542 --> 02:23.110
<i>are practically synonymous.</i>

02:23.211 --> 02:27.147
<i>Of course, had we only
foreseen this crisis,</i>

02:27.248 --> 02:30.250
<i>we might, by now,
be so much further down</i>

02:30.251 --> 02:33.487
<i>the figurative road on the way
to energy independence.</i>

02:33.587 --> 02:35.523
<i>- ♪ quiet, dramatic music</i>
- [monitor beeping]

02:35.856 --> 02:38.559
<i>***</i>

02:48.636 --> 02:50.338
[Cami speaking indistinctly]

02:50.438 --> 02:51.372
Cami?

02:51.472 --> 02:52.506
[sighs]

02:52.640 --> 02:55.075
- Hey.
- [sighs]

02:57.110 --> 02:59.111
- Alan.
- Tommy.

02:59.112 --> 03:00.447
So, what do we know?

03:00.448 --> 03:01.948
Well, we don't know anything.

03:01.949 --> 03:04.984
Uh, he was already in surgery
when we got here.

03:04.985 --> 03:07.521
Cardiologist said
a dietician found him

03:07.621 --> 03:09.056
on the floor unresponsive.

03:09.156 --> 03:12.560
They got him stabilized,
and here we are.

03:13.694 --> 03:16.830
Nothing to do but wait and pray.

03:16.930 --> 03:18.065
There are some things
we should discuss

03:18.198 --> 03:20.132
if those prayers
aren't answered.

03:20.133 --> 03:21.869
All right.

03:32.613 --> 03:34.715
Well, Monty's will states that,

03:34.815 --> 03:38.419
upon his death
or incapacitation,

03:38.519 --> 03:41.153
you are to be made president,

03:41.154 --> 03:44.858
and facilitate
the sale of the company.

03:44.958 --> 03:48.262
The proceeds are to be split
between a foundation,

03:48.362 --> 03:50.898
which Cami will run,

03:50.998 --> 03:53.367
and a trust,
which you will serve

03:53.467 --> 03:55.235
as executor.

03:56.870 --> 03:58.170
Monty's fighting for his life.

03:58.171 --> 04:00.073
We can look at that later
if he loses,

04:00.173 --> 04:03.076
but right now,
let's focus on the win, okay?

04:04.478 --> 04:06.846
Well, whether he lives or dies,

04:06.847 --> 04:10.318
he is incapacitated.

04:11.352 --> 04:14.020
And there's
a $167 million dollar farm-out

04:14.021 --> 04:15.789
that's waiting to be executed.

04:17.257 --> 04:19.259
He needs
a heart transplant, Tommy.

04:20.861 --> 04:22.062
Is that what they're doing?

04:22.162 --> 04:23.297
[Alan]
Well, they're trying to get him

04:23.431 --> 04:26.065
stable enough to receive one.

04:26.066 --> 04:28.602
They won't risk the organ
on a recipient

04:28.702 --> 04:30.571
that isn't healthy enough

04:30.671 --> 04:32.905
to survive the procedure,

04:32.906 --> 04:36.944
much less the body's reaction
to a foreign organ.

04:37.077 --> 04:39.613
He is already incapacitated,

04:39.713 --> 04:43.551
and he will stay that way
for the foreseeable future.

04:47.788 --> 04:49.289
Will you accept the position

04:49.390 --> 04:52.560
as president of M-TEX Oil
and the family estate?

04:55.863 --> 04:56.764
Yes.

04:56.864 --> 04:58.230
[Alan]
And will you

04:58.231 --> 05:01.068
accept the role
as executor of the family trust?

05:02.370 --> 05:05.339
Yes, but I want a board
with both of you on it.

05:05.439 --> 05:06.807
Yeah, that's fine.

05:07.741 --> 05:09.209
Cami?

05:10.077 --> 05:11.278
Well, what does that mean?

05:11.379 --> 05:13.947
It means you vote
on the decisions I make.

05:14.047 --> 05:16.583
And who else
is on the board besides us?

05:16.584 --> 05:18.652
- Who manages his money?
- Goldman.

05:18.786 --> 05:20.821
Okay, somebody from Goldman.

05:20.921 --> 05:21.855
Okay.

05:21.989 --> 05:23.089
Talk to me about this farm-out.

05:23.090 --> 05:25.826
Well, look, it's...

05:25.926 --> 05:27.661
The lease holder
is over-leveraged

05:27.761 --> 05:29.329
and can't raise the capital.

05:29.430 --> 05:30.831
Field's rich.

05:30.931 --> 05:34.034
We recoup our expenses
before an 80/20 split

05:34.167 --> 05:36.436
that settles at 65/35.

05:36.437 --> 05:38.672
It can be a 10X deal, assuming

05:38.772 --> 05:41.909
we increase our production,
which I believe we can.

05:43.744 --> 05:45.478
What's the worst-case scenario?

05:45.479 --> 05:47.180
Worst case?

05:47.314 --> 05:51.585
Worst case is another COVID
or OPEC floods the market,

05:51.685 --> 05:53.186
oil drops below 60

05:53.286 --> 05:55.355
and puts us out of business
in a year.

05:56.457 --> 05:59.492
Hmm. And what's best case?

05:59.493 --> 06:03.496
$1.2, $1.4 billion dollars
in 48 months.

06:03.497 --> 06:04.964
Or do what Monty would do

06:04.965 --> 06:07.535
and sell the paper for
800 million in six months

06:07.635 --> 06:09.036
and go find the next one.

06:09.136 --> 06:10.370
[scoffs]

06:10.504 --> 06:13.240
Well, there aren't any more
next ones, Tommy.

06:14.442 --> 06:15.642
Can you sell it now?

06:15.643 --> 06:17.010
It's worthless till we drill.

06:17.110 --> 06:18.378
I could blow up the deal,

06:18.479 --> 06:19.747
and then whatever he has now

06:19.847 --> 06:21.549
is what they have going forward.

06:23.517 --> 06:25.786
He set aside for you,
I know he did.

06:31.659 --> 06:33.126
Cami.

06:33.226 --> 06:35.395
You don't need a foundation.

06:35.496 --> 06:36.863
Let's sell this thing now.

06:36.864 --> 06:39.600
Your kids' kids will
never have to work.

06:43.737 --> 06:46.807
And then what? Then what, Tommy?

07:01.188 --> 07:03.523
You know, all he wanted
is to be remembered.

07:03.524 --> 07:05.626
That's it.

07:05.726 --> 07:07.094
Not for the money...

07:08.261 --> 07:11.198
...but for
what we do with the money.

07:15.168 --> 07:18.238
And, yeah...

07:18.338 --> 07:21.642
I-I have enough
to live and live well.

07:24.211 --> 07:27.815
But do I have enough
to make the world remember him?

07:27.948 --> 07:30.550
Well, sell the fucking plane.

07:30.551 --> 07:33.219
You can build a hell of
a high school football stadium.

07:33.220 --> 07:36.123
I don't know
what to tell you, Cami.

07:39.292 --> 07:41.294
I'm sorry.

07:44.197 --> 07:46.133
It's just...

07:46.266 --> 07:48.001
That's what's killing him,

07:48.135 --> 07:49.569
trying to be immortal.

07:49.570 --> 07:52.272
You want it to kill you, too?

07:54.908 --> 07:57.110
You have 200 million bucks
laying around?

07:57.210 --> 07:59.146
No, I don't. [sniffles]

07:59.246 --> 08:02.449
Okay, so we get a loan.
Because of the risk,

08:02.550 --> 08:04.917
it's prohibitive.
That's 12 to 14%

08:04.918 --> 08:06.887
that you have
to personally guarantee.

08:06.987 --> 08:09.122
That means the house
and the ranch

08:09.222 --> 08:11.124
and the place in Aspen,

08:11.224 --> 08:13.293
all that shit.

08:13.393 --> 08:16.163
There's way more oil men
who went bankrupt

08:16.263 --> 08:20.167
than became billionaires.

08:20.267 --> 08:22.102
This is that kind of deal.

08:23.403 --> 08:24.971
[footsteps approaching]

08:24.972 --> 08:27.174
Here comes the doctor.

08:27.975 --> 08:29.843
- Cami?
- Yeah.

08:29.943 --> 08:33.681
Monty suffered
a ruptured aortic aneurysm,

08:33.781 --> 08:35.348
which is a tear
of the aortic wall

08:35.448 --> 08:37.718
which causes internal bleeding
at a very rapid rate.

08:37.818 --> 08:40.353
Because of the size
and nature of the rupture,

08:40.453 --> 08:42.590
we were required
to do open surgery.

08:42.690 --> 08:45.358
We removed the damaged
portion of the aorta.

08:45.458 --> 08:46.994
We replaced it with a graft.

08:47.094 --> 08:49.863
We have him on an extracorporeal
membrane oxygenation machine,

08:49.997 --> 08:52.900
which pumps and oxygenates his
blood while his heart recovers.

08:53.000 --> 08:55.535
At this point,
the best option is a transplant.

08:55.669 --> 08:59.138
Once he's stable enough,
we will seek a donor.

08:59.139 --> 09:01.341
Okay, um... chances?

09:01.441 --> 09:03.677
Wh-What are his chances?

09:03.777 --> 09:05.177
[doctor]
If we can find a donor

09:05.178 --> 09:06.847
in the near future,
the chances are good.

09:06.947 --> 09:10.349
One-year survival rates
are over 70%.

09:10.350 --> 09:12.953
But we are on a clock.

09:13.053 --> 09:15.122
We need the organ
sooner than later.

09:16.156 --> 09:19.627
And how long can he
survive without it?

09:20.393 --> 09:21.962
There's no way to gauge that.

09:22.062 --> 09:24.031
If he can make it two weeks,

09:24.131 --> 09:26.833
I feel pretty good
about our chances.

09:26.834 --> 09:28.435
When can I see him?

09:28.568 --> 09:31.038
Let's get through
the next 24 hours, okay?

09:31.138 --> 09:33.840
If there's any change
in his condition,

09:33.841 --> 09:36.276
I will let you know.

09:46.286 --> 09:49.890
You want to know the last
thing that I said to him?

09:55.595 --> 09:58.031
"You need a shave."

10:01.434 --> 10:03.771
28 years of marriage,

10:03.871 --> 10:05.404
and the last thing
I said to him is

10:05.405 --> 10:08.275
you need a fucking shave.

10:12.079 --> 10:13.613
[sighs]

10:23.056 --> 10:24.792
<i>♪ gentle music ♪</i>

10:25.058 --> 10:27.227
<i>***</i>

10:45.913 --> 10:48.348
<i>***</i>

11:09.169 --> 11:11.538
<i>***</i>

11:31.491 --> 11:33.226
<i>♪ percussive music ♪</i>

11:33.560 --> 11:36.196
<i>***</i>

11:56.483 --> 11:58.618
<i>***</i>

12:17.170 --> 12:19.439
[phone buzzing]

12:22.675 --> 12:24.444
- Yeah.
- It's gone.

12:24.577 --> 12:25.946
- What did I tell you?
<i>- No.</i>

12:26.079 --> 12:27.480
The whole fucking thing.

12:28.248 --> 12:30.283
The van, the tire tracks, everything.

12:30.383 --> 12:33.921
[sighs]
What did I fucking tell you?

12:34.021 --> 12:35.789
<i>So now what?</i>

12:35.923 --> 12:36.756
Now nothing.

12:36.857 --> 12:38.391
Nothing for you.

12:38.491 --> 12:40.127
I've got two freaked out pilots

12:40.227 --> 12:42.662
and a mortar crew wanting
to call fucking lawyers.

12:42.762 --> 12:44.563
[sighs]

12:44.564 --> 12:47.100
All right, give me two minutes.

13:10.858 --> 13:12.359
[line ringing]

13:13.226 --> 13:14.161
Yeah.

13:14.261 --> 13:15.462
Isn't everything you guys do

13:15.562 --> 13:16.763
supposed to be classified?

13:16.864 --> 13:18.264
What am I, a fucking Navy SEAL?

13:18.265 --> 13:20.066
<i>We're a National Guard unit,
Tommy.</i>

13:20.067 --> 13:22.702
<i>These guys are auto mechanics
and insurance salesmen.</i>

13:22.802 --> 13:24.436
Well, let me tell you something, bud.

13:24.437 --> 13:26.438
<i>They're gonna look
pretty fucking dumb</i>

13:26.439 --> 13:27.774
<i>confessing to a crime</i>

13:27.875 --> 13:29.476
<i>where there's
no fucking evidence</i>

13:29.576 --> 13:31.711
and no fucking witnesses
and, most important,

13:31.811 --> 13:33.446
no fucking victim.

13:33.546 --> 13:36.748
I would suggest that everybody
get amnesia real fucking fast.

13:36.749 --> 13:38.385
We on the same page?

13:39.219 --> 13:40.487
Yeah, I'll talk to 'em.

13:40.587 --> 13:41.821
I recommend it.

13:41.922 --> 13:43.556
Bye.

13:43.656 --> 13:45.993
[sighs]

13:47.660 --> 13:49.529
<i>♪ somber music ♪</i>

13:49.796 --> 13:51.564
<i>***</i>

13:51.664 --> 13:54.001
[sighs]

14:08.115 --> 14:10.782
I want to say something
to you about faith and hope

14:10.783 --> 14:13.586
and all that, but...

14:15.122 --> 14:19.459
...since I don't believe in it,
it's kind of hard to ask you to.

14:20.360 --> 14:21.861
But I will say this.

14:21.962 --> 14:26.233
Monty is the luckiest man
I've ever known in my life.

14:27.634 --> 14:31.371
He wins when everybody,
and I mean everybody, loses.

14:33.773 --> 14:36.609
So if I was still
a betting man...

14:37.610 --> 14:40.313
...I'd bet on him
pulling through.

14:42.215 --> 14:44.317
Still smoking, huh?

14:47.988 --> 14:50.156
You're still a betting man

14:50.157 --> 14:51.925
every day.

14:53.826 --> 14:56.263
Now go and make a bet for me.

14:56.396 --> 14:58.065
Close the farm-out.

14:58.165 --> 15:01.268
And we roll the dice
one last time.

15:05.372 --> 15:07.274
<i>[motorcycle engine revving
in song]</i>

15:07.407 --> 15:08.874
<i>♪ "Girls, Girls, Girls"
by Mötley Crüe ♪</i>

15:08.875 --> 15:10.043
<i>♪ Whoo! ♪</i>

15:10.143 --> 15:11.979
<i>♪ Ha-ha ♪</i>

15:15.515 --> 15:17.417
<i>♪ Mm, mm ♪</i>

15:18.585 --> 15:20.787
[whooping]

15:23.223 --> 15:24.958
<i>***</i>

15:35.068 --> 15:36.403
<i>♪ Friday night ♪</i>

15:36.503 --> 15:38.638
<i>- ♪ And I need a fight</i>
- [whooping]

15:38.771 --> 15:41.474
<i>♪ My motorcycle
and a switchblade knife... ♪</i>

15:41.574 --> 15:43.610
Oh, shit, I forgot.

15:45.045 --> 15:46.545
Here.

15:46.546 --> 15:48.081
- [chuckles]
- Oh.

15:48.181 --> 15:49.249
Load 'em up.

15:49.349 --> 15:50.483
[Ainsley]
That's a lot of 20s.

15:50.583 --> 15:51.484
<i>♪ Girls, girls, girls... ♪</i>

15:51.618 --> 15:52.952
Here, Bob. Here, babe.

15:53.053 --> 15:56.289
- Now we're talking. [chuckles]
- [chuckles]

15:56.389 --> 15:57.389
[Angela]
Oh, no, baby.

15:57.390 --> 15:59.558
Baby, you got to ration it, Bob.

15:59.559 --> 16:01.328
This is all you get.

16:02.262 --> 16:05.132
<i>♪ Girls, girls, girls... ♪</i>

16:06.133 --> 16:07.467
[Ainsley]
What do you think?

16:07.567 --> 16:09.369
[Ethel]
What do I think?

16:10.303 --> 16:13.640
What do I think about these
skinny bitches reminding me

16:13.773 --> 16:15.475
of what I can't do anymore?

16:15.575 --> 16:16.976
What do you think I think?

16:17.077 --> 16:19.312
Well, I have a dancer
for you, too, Ethel.

16:19.446 --> 16:20.980
[scoffs]
Right.

16:21.114 --> 16:22.248
I do.

16:22.249 --> 16:23.650
Well, why are
you hiding him, then?

16:23.750 --> 16:25.251
Okay, just give me a minute.

16:25.252 --> 16:27.619
You're gonna be real excited,
Ethel. [chuckles]

16:27.620 --> 16:28.788
I doubt it.

16:28.888 --> 16:30.289
- [Ethel scoffs, mutters]
- [Ainsley laughs]

16:30.290 --> 16:31.623
Go get him.

16:31.624 --> 16:33.360
[exhales sharply]

16:34.261 --> 16:35.695
This is...

16:35.828 --> 16:37.164
this is...

16:37.264 --> 16:38.631
- this is...
- [Jasmine] First time can be

16:38.731 --> 16:40.200
pretty nerve-racking,
but after that,

16:40.333 --> 16:41.534
it can be really fun.

16:41.668 --> 16:42.835
You should do a shot of vodka.

16:42.935 --> 16:44.637
Loosen the nerves.

16:46.273 --> 16:48.675
It's 11 in the morning.

16:48.775 --> 16:50.843
I have football practice.

16:50.943 --> 16:52.978
- How old are you?
- Does it matter?

16:52.979 --> 16:55.515
State of Texas
is pretty picky about it.

16:55.615 --> 16:57.517
- [sighs]
- Babe.

16:59.919 --> 17:00.986
We need you out there.

17:00.987 --> 17:02.589
It's your time to shine.

17:03.890 --> 17:07.494
There's only 20 minutes before
their nap, so it won't be long.

17:07.594 --> 17:10.029
I-I'm having second thoughts.

17:10.163 --> 17:11.364
But we had a deal.

17:11.464 --> 17:12.831
[sighs]

17:12.832 --> 17:15.167
And you're getting
the better end of it.

17:15.168 --> 17:18.504
Remember,
whatever you do for them,

